{%- comment -%}
  The design tokens the journal CARD is drawn from. Shared, because the card itself is shared:
  snippets/dev-journal-cards-card.liquid renders the markup, assets/dev-journal-cards.css styles it,
  and this declares the values both of them read.

  Two places render that card:
    * sections/dev-journal-cards.liquid   — the "The coded language of bedding" strip on Our Story
    * sections/dev-blog.liquid            — the /blogs/<handle> index

  They MUST look identical: a reader clicking from the strip to the index and back should not see
  the card change. Copying this block into the second section would have guaranteed the opposite —
  the two would drift the first time anyone touched one of them.

  The card CSS targets unscoped classes (.journal-cards__card, __badge, __meta …), so the tokens
  only need to live on some ancestor. Hence `scope`: each caller passes the selector of its own
  root, and the cards inside inherit.

  @param {string} scope - CSS selector of the calling section's root, e.g. '.journal-cards'
{%- endcomment -%}

<style>
  {{ scope }} {
    /* Brand params (Brief → Brand Params). Faces are loaded by snippets/dev-brand-fonts.liquid. */
    /* The Figma content frame is 1440 − 2×64 = 1312. This used to read 100% — the frame described
       as the section's padding box rather than a cap of its own — which is true up to 1440 and
       nothing but true up to 1440: past it the row simply kept growing with the window and the
       three cards stretched with it. 1312 is the same number the artboard draws, now enforced.

       Both callers already centre on this (.journal-cards__inner and .dev-blog__inner are
       `max-width: var(--container-max); margin-inline: auto`), so the one value caps both — which
       is the point of this file. Capping only the Our Story strip would have made a card there a
       different width from the same card on the blog index at >1440, and a reader clicking
       between the two would see it change. */
    --container-max: 1312px;
    --section-px: 64px;
    --section-px-m: 16px;

    /* Typography — desktop */
    --font-heading-size: 32px;
    --font-heading-weight: 500;
    --font-heading-lh: 1.2;
    --font-body-size: 14px;
    --font-body-weight: 400;
    --font-body-lh: 1.4;

    /* Typography — mobile: read off the Mobile artboard, not a scale factor. */
    --font-heading-size-m: 24px;
    --font-body-size-m: 12px;

    /* Card */
    --card-heading-size: 20px;
    --card-heading-weight: 500;
    --card-heading-lh: 1.2;
    --card-image-h: 220px;
    --card-image-h-m: 150px;
    --card-content-py: 16px;
    --radius-card: 16px;

    /* Badge */
    --badge-bg: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.9);
    --badge-color: #000000;
    --badge-font-size: 13px;
    --badge-font-weight: 500;
    --badge-lh: 1.4;
    --badge-px: 12px;
    --badge-py: 6px;
    --radius-badge: 4px;

    /* CTA */
    --cta-font-size: 16px;
    --cta-font-weight: 700;
    --cta-lh: 1.4;
    --cta-icon-gap: 4px;
    --cta-icon-size: 24px;

    /* Spacing */
    --spacing-sm: 12px;
    --spacing-md: 24px;
    --spacing-lg: 32px;
    --spacing-md-m: 16px;
    --spacing-lg-m: 24px;
  }
</style>
